	<div class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 vcard parent highlander-comment" id="comment-459934">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2015/09/29/275a-notes-0-foundations-of-probability-theory/#comment-459934" title="Permalink to this comment">1 October, 2015 at 3:29 pm</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">Chris</strong></p>
					</div>

		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt="" src="https://0.gravatar.com/avatar/337bc38a1307985e127242880fd20105?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG" class="avatar avatar-32 grav-hashed grav-hijack" height="32" width="32" id="grav-337bc38a1307985e127242880fd20105-0">			<p>From the measure-theoretic point of view a “random variable” $X$ is considered as a deterministic function (as defined above). On the other hand, in practice one often just writes something like $X \sim N(\mu,\sigma)$ to signify the random variable is distributed as the normal distribution for example, say, without reference to any sample spaces. The above corollary shows this suffices in practices as only the CDF really matters. The question that has always been a bit of a puzzle from a foundations point of view is how to interpret the randomness of the so-called random variable? How does the random variable modelling, say, a coin toss as an explicit function from a sample space fit with the practice of generating a coin toss, either by computer or with physical coins (which is determined by the CDF)? A related corollary issue come with the related concept of a “statistic”, which is taken to be some function of a random variable or several such, and what can be realised/explicitly calculated from a given set of data.</p>
<div class="pd-rating" id="pd_rating_holder_132742_comm_459934" style="display: inline-block;"><div class="rating-icons" id="pd_rate_132742_comm_459934" style="float:left;"><div class="rating-nero-icon" onmouseout="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.rebuild();" onclick="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.rate(1);" onmouseover="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.hover(1);" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934_nero_1" style="background-size: 32px 32px !important; cursor: pointer; width: 16px; height: 16px;  line-height: 16px; background: url(https://polldaddy.com/images/ratings/nero-hand-sml.png) bottom left; float: left; padding: 0px; margin: 0px; margin: 0px;">&nbsp;</div><div class="rating-nero-value" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934_msg_1" style="text-align: center; font:normal normal /16px ; color: #; float:left; padding: 0px 4px;">5</div><div class="rating-nero-icon" onmouseout="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.rebuild();" onclick="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.rate(2);" onmouseover="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.hover(2);" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934_nero_2" style="background-size: 32px 32px !important; cursor: pointer; width: 16px; height: 16px;  line-height: 16px; background: url(https://polldaddy.com/images/ratings/nero-hand-sml.png) bottom right; float: left; padding: 0px; margin: 0px; margin: 0px;">&nbsp;</div><div class="rating-nero-value" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934_msg_2" style="text-align: center; font:normal normal /16px ; color: #; float:left; padding: 0px 4px;">0</div></div><span style="float:left;">&nbsp;</span><div id="rating_info_132742_comm_459934" style="display:block;float:left;background:url(https://polldaddy.com/images/ratings/info.png) no-repeat 3px 2px;width:16px;height:16px;cursor:pointer; null " onclick="javascript:PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934.togglePopup();return false;"><span style="display:none;">i</span></div><div class="pd_popup_holder" id="pd_popup_holder_132742_comm_459934">&nbsp;</div><div class="rating-msg" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_459934_msg" style="float:left; padding-left: 5px; text-align: left; font:normal normal /16px ; color: #;">Rate This</div><p style="padding: 0px; margin: 0px; clear: both;"></p></div>
<script type="text/javascript" charset="UTF-8"><!--//--><![CDATA[//><!--
PDRTJS_settings_132742_comm_459934={"id":132742,"unique_id":"wp-comment-459934","title":"From%20the%20measure-theoretic%20point%20of%20view%20a%20%26quot%3Brandom%20variable%26quot%3B%20%24X%24%20is%20considered%20as%20a%20deterministic%20function%20%28as%20defined%20above%29.%20On%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20in%20practice%20one%20often%20just%20writes%20something%20like%20...","permalink":"https:\/\/terrytao.wordpress.com\/2015\/09\/29\/275a-notes-0-foundations-of-probability-theory\/#comment-459934","item_id":"_comm_459934"};
