	<div class="comment odd alt depth-4 vcard parent highlander-comment" id="comment-474369">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2015/09/29/275a-notes-0-foundations-of-probability-theory/#comment-474369" title="Permalink to this comment">14 November, 2016 at 12:46 pm</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">Anonymous</strong></p>
					</div>

		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt="" src="https://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG" class="avatar avatar-32 grav-hashed grav-hijack" height="32" width="32" id="grav-false-12">			<p>I have confusion about your comments. </p>
<p>(I) an “event” <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=E&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=545454&amp;s=0" alt="E" title="E" class="latex"> “does not have to” be a set.</p>
<p>(II)”the only requirement is that the events lie in an abstract sigma algebra equipped with a probability measure”</p>
<p>Would you elaborate what you mean by “abstract sigma algebra”? Isn’t a sigma algebra is a collection of subsets of a given set with the sigma algebra structure and thus any element lies in an abstract sigma algebra must be a “set”? (if an event <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=E&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=545454&amp;s=0" alt="E" title="E" class="latex">  is not a set, would you give an example to illustrate what else it could be?)</p>
<p>I’m also not very clear about the analogy with vectors in a finite-dimensional space. Suppose <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=V&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=545454&amp;s=0" alt="V" title="V" class="latex"> is a real vector space of dimension <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=545454&amp;s=0" alt="2" title="2" class="latex">. Then a model for <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=V&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=545454&amp;s=0" alt="V" title="V" class="latex"> is <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=545454&amp;s=0" alt="\mathbb{R}^2" title="\mathbb{R}^2" class="latex">. But isn’t it true that the abstract vector space $V$ itself is also a “set” in the first place by definition?</p>
<div class="pd-rating" id="pd_rating_holder_132742_comm_474369" style="display: inline-block;"><div class="rating-icons" id="pd_rate_132742_comm_474369" style="float:left;"><div class="rating-nero-icon" onmouseout="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.rebuild();" onclick="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.rate(1);" onmouseover="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.hover(1);" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369_nero_1" style="background-size: 32px 32px !important; cursor: pointer; width: 16px; height: 16px;  line-height: 16px; background: url(https://polldaddy.com/images/ratings/nero-hand-sml.png) bottom left; float: left; padding: 0px; margin: 0px; margin: 0px;">&nbsp;</div><div class="rating-nero-value" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369_msg_1" style="text-align: center; font:normal normal /16px ; color: #; float:left; padding: 0px 4px;">0</div><div class="rating-nero-icon" onmouseout="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.rebuild();" onclick="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.rate(2);" onmouseover="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.hover(2);" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369_nero_2" style="background-size: 32px 32px !important; cursor: pointer; width: 16px; height: 16px;  line-height: 16px; background: url(https://polldaddy.com/images/ratings/nero-hand-sml.png) bottom right; float: left; padding: 0px; margin: 0px; margin: 0px;">&nbsp;</div><div class="rating-nero-value" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369_msg_2" style="text-align: center; font:normal normal /16px ; color: #; float:left; padding: 0px 4px;">0</div></div><span style="float:left;">&nbsp;</span><div id="rating_info_132742_comm_474369" style="display:block;float:left;background:url(https://polldaddy.com/images/ratings/info.png) no-repeat 3px 2px;width:16px;height:16px;cursor:pointer; null " onclick="javascript:PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369.togglePopup();return false;"><span style="display:none;">i</span></div><div class="pd_popup_holder" id="pd_popup_holder_132742_comm_474369">&nbsp;</div><div class="rating-msg" id="PDRTJS_132742_comm_474369_msg" style="float:left; padding-left: 5px; text-align: left; font:normal normal /16px ; color: #;">Rate This</div><p style="padding: 0px; margin: 0px; clear: both;"></p></div>
<script type="text/javascript" charset="UTF-8"><!--//--><![CDATA[//><!--
PDRTJS_settings_132742_comm_474369={"id":132742,"unique_id":"wp-comment-474369","title":"I%20have%20confusion%20about%20your%20comments.%20%28I%29%20an%20%26quot%3Bevent%26quot%3B%20%24latex%20E%24%20%26quot%3Bdoes%20not%20have%20to%26quot%3B%20be%20a%20set.%28II%29%26quot%3Bthe%20only%20requirement%20is%20that%20the%20events%20lie%20in%20an%20abstract%20sigma%20algebra%20equipped%20with%20a%20probabilit...","permalink":"https:\/\/terrytao.wordpress.com\/2015\/09\/29\/275a-notes-0-foundations-of-probability-theory\/#comment-474369","item_id":"_comm_474369"};
